Instead of: find . -name "*.nix"
Try:        fd "*.nix"
fd is faster, has simpler syntax, and respects .gitignore
%
Instead of: grep -r "pattern" .
Try:        rg "pattern"  (grep is aliased to rg)
ripgrep is faster and respects .gitignore by default
%
Instead of: du -sh *
Try:        dust  (du is aliased to dust)
dust shows a visual tree of disk usage, sorted by size
%
Instead of: df -h
Try:        duf  (df is aliased to duf)
duf shows disk space in a clean, colored table layout
%
Instead of: ps aux | grep process
Try:        procs process  (ps is aliased to procs)
procs has built-in search, tree view, and colored output
%
Instead of: dig example.com
Try:        doggo example.com  (dig is aliased to doggo)
doggo shows DNS results in a clean, colored table with JSON output
%
Instead of: diff file1 file2
Try:        difft file1 file2  (diff is aliased to difft)
difftastic understands syntax -- shows structural, not just text diffs
%
Instead of: traceroute example.com
Try:        mtr example.com  (traceroute is aliased to mtr)
mtr combines traceroute + ping with live updating statistics
%
Instead of: top (or htop)
Try:        btop  (top and htop are aliased to btop)
btop has graphs, mouse support, and per-process network/disk I/O
%
Instead of: cloc .
Try:        tokei  (cloc is aliased to tokei)
tokei counts lines of code by language, 10x faster than cloc
%
Instead of: history | grep ssh
Try:        hg ssh
hg searches your ENTIRE history (100k entries), not just the last 16
%
Instead of: command --help | less
Try:        help command
Pipes --help through bat for syntax highlighting and automatic paging
%
Instead of: tar xzf file.tar.gz (or unzip, 7z x...)
Try:        extract file.tar.gz
extract auto-detects format: tar, zip, 7z, rar, bz2, xz, and more
%
Instead of: git branch -a, then git checkout branch-name
Try:        fco
Fuzzy-searchable branch picker -- type to filter local + remote branches
%
Instead of: git log --oneline, find commit, git show SHA
Try:        flog
Interactive commit browser with inline diff preview via fzf
%
Instead of: man command (wall of plain text)
Your man pages now have syntax highlighting automatically via bat
The MANPAGER is set -- just use man normally and enjoy the colors
%
Instead of: cd ~/some/deep/frequently/used/path
Try:        z path  (or z deep, or z freq)
zoxide learns your habits -- partial names work after visiting once
%
Ctrl+T opens a fuzzy file picker with bat preview
Browse files with syntax-highlighted preview, Enter inserts the path
Works anywhere on the command line -- type a partial command first
%
Alt+C opens a fuzzy directory picker with tree preview
Browse directories with eza tree preview, Enter to cd into it
Much faster than cd + tab-completing deep paths
%
Ctrl+R opens fuzzy history search via fzf
Type any fragment of a past command to filter instantly
Much faster than pressing up-arrow repeatedly
%
Press ESC twice to prepend sudo to your last command
This is the oh-my-zsh "sudo" plugin -- no need to retype anything
Works on the current command line too, not just history
%
Type acs to search all your shell aliases
The oh-my-zsh "aliases" plugin lets you discover shortcuts
Example: acs kubectl  shows all kubectl-related aliases
%
shelp shows your complete tool/alias/function reference
shelp KEYWORD filters it: try shelp git, shelp replace, shelp fzf
This is your single source of truth for what's installed
%
sd is simpler than sed for find/replace
Example: sd 'old_text' 'new_text' file.txt
No regex escaping headaches -- just two strings and a file
%
xh is a friendlier HTTP client than curl
Example: xh httpbin.org/get  or  xh POST api.example.com key=value
Colored output, auto-formatted JSON, easy headers with key:value
%
glow renders markdown beautifully in your terminal
Example: glow README.md
Great for reading docs, changelogs, and notes without leaving the shell
%
tldr gives you simplified, example-based help for any command
Example: tldr tar  (shows the 5 most common tar patterns)
Much faster than reading full man pages when you just need examples
%
hyperfine benchmarks commands with statistical rigor
Example: hyperfine 'fd -e nix' 'find . -name "*.nix"'
Runs multiple iterations and shows min/mean/max with comparison
%
gdu is a colored alternative to ncdu for interactive disk usage
Navigate with arrow keys, press d to delete files, q to quit
Also try: dua i  for a Rust-based alternative (extremely fast scanning)
%
bat --diff file.txt shows git changes inline
Highlights added/removed lines compared to the git index
Combine with --style=changes for a minimal diff view
%
fd can filter by extension: fd -e nix
Or by type: fd -t d (directories only), fd -t f (files only)
Add -H to include hidden files, -I to ignore .gitignore
%
rg can search specific file types: rg "pattern" -t nix
Combine with -l for just filenames, -c for counts
Add -i for case-insensitive, --no-ignore to search gitignored files
%
dust -r reverses the sort (smallest first)
dust -n 10 limits output to top 10 entries
dust -d 2 limits directory depth
%
procs --tree shows process hierarchy
procs --sortd cpu sorts by CPU usage descending
procs -w shows full command lines without truncation
%
In tmux: prefix + Space shows a shortcut cheat sheet
All common tmux operations in one menu -- splits, windows, sessions
No more forgetting which key does what
%
In tmux: prefix + t activates tmux-thumbs
Highlights URLs, paths, hashes, IPs on screen -- press a hint to copy
Much faster than selecting text with the mouse
%
In tmux: prefix + S creates a new named session
prefix + s shows the session/window tree picker
Use sessions to organize different projects
%
In tmux: F12 toggles nested tmux mode for SSH
Status bar dims to gray and all keys pass through to the remote tmux
Press F12 again to switch back to local control
%
Your tmux lock screen picks a random screensaver each time
cmatrix, asciiquarium, cbonsai, pipes.sh, lavat, or tty-clock
Trigger it manually with prefix + L, or wait 15 minutes idle
%
gsa (git-sync-all) is your morning sync command
Fetches, switches to default branch, and pulls all repos in one shot
Run it in your Git.Local directory to update everything at once
%
gsall (git-status-all) checks all repos at once
Quickly see which repos have uncommitted changes or are ahead/behind
Run it before gsa to see what needs attention
%
gi (git-info) shows comprehensive info for the current repo
Branch, remotes, recent commits, stash count, and more in one view
Faster than running multiple git commands separately
%
gc opens commitizen for interactive conventional commits
Walks you through type, scope, and description for consistent format
Much easier than remembering feat/fix/chore/refactor prefixes
%
k is aliased to kubectl -- combine with other shortcuts:
  ka FILE    kubectl apply -f
  kns NAME   set current namespace
  kshell POD exec into a pod interactively
%
direnv auto-loads .envrc files when you cd into a directory
Create a .envrc with export VAR=value, then run: direnv allow
Automatically unloads when you leave the directory
%
Use command <name> to bypass an alias and run the original
Example: command grep uses /usr/bin/grep instead of rg
Example: command du uses the original du instead of dust
%
zoxide keeps a ranked list of your directories
z -l shows the full list with frecency scores
zi opens an interactive fzf picker of your frequent directories
%
bat --list-themes shows all available color themes
Current theme: TwoDark (configured in home/default.nix)
Try: bat --theme=Dracula file.txt to preview a different theme
%
fzf works anywhere -- pipe anything into it for fuzzy selection
Example: rg -l pattern | fzf --preview 'bat --color=always {}'
Example: git stash list | fzf | cut -d: -f1 | xargs git stash show
%
The oh-my-zsh docker and helm plugins add tab completion
Type docker<TAB> or helm<TAB> to see available subcommands
Works for kubectl too (via the kubectl plugin)
%
secure (op-load-secrets) loads env vars from 1Password
Run it once per session to populate API keys and tokens
Secrets stay in memory only -- never written to disk
%
check-updates shows available brew and nix updates
A notification banner appears on shell startup when updates exist
Run: brew upgrade && nix flake update ~/.config/nix && switch
%
Your autosuggestions now prioritize history over completions
The gray ghost text shows commands you've actually run before
Press right-arrow or End to accept, or keep typing to ignore
%
History is now deduplicated -- no more 500 copies of ls
ignoreAllDups removes the older copy when a new duplicate is added
expireDuplicatesFirst removes dupes first when trimming to 100k limit
